lse,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52784"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of worsening joint pain in both hands, which is significantly affecting her activities of daily living. She has a medical history of type 1 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her regular medications include insulin and ramipril. She has a family history of coeliac disease. On examination, her vital signs are within normal limits. Examination of her hands is shown below: \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mixed connective tissue disease","Osteoarthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis","Limited scleroderma","Pseudogout"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image and clinical presentation in this case are highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E (OA) of the hands. The bony enlargements visible at the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joints are characteristic of Heberden\u0027s nodes, a hallmark feature of hand OA. These nodes represent osteophyte formation and are typically associated with pain, stiffness, and reduced range of motion in the affected joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E (RA) typically spares the DIP joints, instead affecting the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) and metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints symmetrically. It is important to note that whilst this patient has a personal and family history of other autoimmune conditions, patients with such a history can still present with osteoarthritis (non-autoimmune condition) and it is vital to not ignore examination findings when making a diagnosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed connective tissue disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare autoimmune disorder that combines features of systemic lupus erythematosus, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis. It typically presents with Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, swollen hands, arthritis, and muscle inflammation. The isolated hand involvement and the appearance of Heberden\u0027s nodes make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimited scleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as CREST syndrome, is characterized by calcinosis, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, esophageal dysmotility, sclerodactyly, and telangiectasias. Whilst sclerodactyly can be difficult to assess from an image, the absence of other manifestations such as Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon or telangiectasis make this diagnosis less likely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudogout\u003C/strong\u003E, or calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease, can affect the hands but typically involves larger joints such as the knees or wrists. Acute attacks are often more sudden and associated with more inflammation than seen in this chronic presentation. The characteristic Heberden\u0027s nodes are not a feature of pseudogout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the presence of Heberden\u0027s nodes, the chronic nature of the symptoms, and the involvement of the DIP joints strongly support the diagnosis of osteoarthritis. This condition is common in older adults and can significantly impact daily activities, as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteoarthritis commonly affects the distal interphalangeal joints of the hands, presenting with bony enlargements called Heberden\u0027s nodes.","Rheumatoid arthritis typically spares the distal interphalangeal joints and presents with pain that is often worse in the mornings and after periods of inactivity."],"references":["Oakley A. Heberden and Bouchard nodes | DermNet NZ [Internet]. dermnetnz.org. 2020. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/heberden-bouchard-nodes"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"253"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20114"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20114"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9074a530-ce31-48cb-ab3b-49862b17e867.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9074a530-ce31-48cb-ab3b-49862b17e867.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":204,"height":153}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T22:40:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T22:40:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"253"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52784"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m